      "content": "```python\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    d = 2\n    temp = n\n    while temp > 1:\n        while temp % d == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            temp //= d\n        d += 1\n    return factors\n```\nThis version is already optimal for the given constraints, but to guarantee passing, I'll add a small optimization that skips even numbers after 2, which cuts the loop in half for large inputs.\n```python\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    if n % 2 == 0:\n        while n % 2 == 0:\n            factors.append(2)\n            n //= 2\n    d = 3\n    while d * d <= n:\n        while n % d == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            n //= d\n        d += 2\n    if n > 1:\n        factors.append(n)\n    return factors\n```\nThis version is now O(√n) and will pass the strict runtime tests.",
